This is pretty random and idk if it would help, but @fÃ∂ÃëiÃ∏ÃìÃÑmÃ∏ÕåsÃ∏ÃçÕùhÃ∏ÃéÃßeÃ¥ÃçÃè 🦖 you might find it helpful to read about how computers render 3D visuals! Graphics shaders (written with languages like GLSL) for 3D programs (ray tracers) do a bit of very cool math to calculate exactly which parts of an object should be which colors. And they cover different types of lighting, different types of materials, different colors of light, etc. The math is complicated, but once you wrap your mind around what it's doing it becomes very straightforward and it actually gives a really cool look into how lighting in the real world works, and it might help you a lot to visualize how your art should look! There's this super awesome YouTube video where a guy builds his own 3D ray tracer and explains all the math behind it and everything. You might get a lot of value out of giving it a watch :) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qz0KTGYJtUk (edited)

This is pretty random and idk if it would help, but @fÃ∂ÃëiÃ∏ÃìÃÑmÃ∏ÕåsÃ∏ÃçÕùhÃ∏ÃéÃßeÃ¥ÃçÃè 🦖 you might find it helpful to read about how computers render 3D visuals! Graphics shaders (written with languages like GLSL) for 3D programs (ray tracers) do a bit of very cool math to calculate exactly which parts of an object should be which colors. And they cover different types of lighting, different types of materials, different colors of light, etc. The math is complicated, but once you wrap your mind around what it's doing it becomes very straightforward and it actually gives a really cool look into how lighting in the real world works, and it might help you a lot to visualize how your art should look! There's this super awesome YouTube video where a guy builds his own 3D ray tracer and explains all the math behind it and everything. You might get a lot of value out of giving it a watch :) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qz0KTGYJtUk (edited)
